      "id": "5ea91a065221d87a",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5ea91a065221d87a",
        "text": "And from here, arguably, a more precise insight into how the spatial and textual labyrinth are laid out and how they form their specific procrastination functions emerges. What is at stake here is not only the transformation of the labyrinthine discourse from myth to narrative model, but the wholesale transformation of the narrative as well as narrative path in general. First, it can be stated that Kafka's labyrinth - geometrically or analytically speaking - is not a winding or tangled path and not an aberration, but not a path at all. This is its new historical and systematic dimension. When Kafka once spoke of there being perhaps a \"goal\" but \"no way\" - \"what we call way is hesitation\" - , this contains an elementary definition of the labyrinthine structure. According to this, the labyrinth is a series of intervals or spatia, or more precisely: it results from infnitesimal divisions, dividing sections into smaller ones and dese into smaller ones again. The labyrinth is an infinite interpolation process, an arbitrary continuation of the continuum. Labyrinthine is a line that stops at each of its points and changes direction, branching and thus becoming discontinuous. Since the nineteenth century, mathematicians have described this with some discomfort as functions that are discontinuous everywhere, as *nowhere differential functions* (Norbert Wiener) that settle into a \"monstrous oscillation\" and remain wholly unmanifest: The path or continuum is no longer, as with Aristotle, that which is indivisible and traversed in one go, from beginning to end; its line is rather scanned point by point and leads to a kind of permanent occupation with any interval, no matter how small."
