      "id": "e3d5968189e3ebc9",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e3d5968189e3ebc9",
        "text": "This fissuring or atomization of the continuum can be grasped with a paradox formulated by the mathematician Hermann Hankel in 1870, which looks like an illustration of Kafka's labyrinth. According to this paradox, a square of side length 1 is divided by horizontal and vertical parallels of equal distance into a grid of small squares. If one takes the path from the lower left corner of the square to the upper right corner, the distance covered – whether one chooses the baseline and the right side line or another course – is always = 2. If one now chooses a path which leads upwards in a staircase as close as possible to the diagonal and if one also lets the number of squares in the net grow to infinity, the infinitely stepped curve apparently coincides with the diagonal and then results in the absurdity: the distance covered by the staircase curve is still = 2, but at the same time=✓2, i.e. the path of the diagonal. In fact, however, the boundary curve of the staircase curve is of a completely different nature: While the tangent of the diagonal has the same value or angle for all its points, the tangent of the stepped boundary curve varies in each of its points in any interval between 0° and 90°. Thus, at none of its points can the boundary curve be assigned a particular direction. Its length is not only different from the path of the diagonal, but at each of its infinite points its course and direction itself are at stake (cf. fig. 3). This results in the labyrinth of a line that \"errs\" in all its points, branches out and interrupts the continuation of its path, a permanent dithering of the course. As little as the threshold space of Kafka's Schloß corresponds to a geometry of spatial extension, it obviously converges with the problems of modern calculus. And perhaps - besides Kafka and modern mathematics - only Paul Klee has attempted a graph for this labyrinth of lines (fig. 4)."
